Part 3

The lawyer's name was Bannerjee. He had a small, dusty office in Dalhousie Square that smelled of red tape, old cardboard, and damp sheepskin folders. 

He arrived at the Bagbazar house on a Saturday morning, his black leather briefcase bulging with three copies of the corporate transfer deed.

"This is the second time we are doing this, Vikram babu," Bannerjee said, setting the thick papers on the green register table. 

Ananya was standing near the well, holding her broom. She had stopped sweeping and was looking at the white paper documents, her eyes moving slowly from the lawyer's clean cuffs to Vikram's hand.

"The second time is easier," Vikram said, picking up the pen.

"It is never easier," Bannerjee said. "The first time, it was family. Your brother Rohan. This time, it is an employee—a boy who has been here only four years. The board will ask questions. The international donors will want to know why the founder is walking away."

"The founder is tired," Vikram said.

He signed. His signature didn't have the sharp, clear 'A' it used to have in Odisha. It was looser, the ink from the ballpoint pen running slightly at the edge of the 'V', leaving a small blue blur on the white bond paper.

Ramu's nephew brought the tea in mismatched glasses. It was red tea, but today the palm sugar was missing from the kitchen; it was just hot ginger and water. 

Bannerjee drank his tea quickly, packed the signed deeds into his leather bag, and stood up. "Rehman has the power now. The banking, the Barasat unit, the international funds. He is the CEO."

"Good," Vikram said.

---

Vikram fell sick three days later. It was the winter cough, the cold fog from the Hooghly river settling deep in his chest, making every breath sound like the dry regulator hiss from his father's room. 

He stayed on his wooden bench in the side room, staring at the ceiling. Sarita brought him hot barley water twice a day, her cane tapping on the stone floor.

"Rehman hasn't come," she said on the fourth morning, setting the cup on the stool.

"He is busy with the Barasat audit, Sarita," Vikram said.

"He is in Alipore, Vikram. The office supervisor said the silver sedan was parked outside the administrative building for three hours yesterday. But he didn't come up to see the patients."

"Let him be," Vikram said. "The new shoes take time to fit."

---

The phone near the register table rang at seven that evening. Vikram was alone in the room. 

He walked out, his legs slightly stiff from the fever, and picked up the black receiver.

"Uncle," a voice said.

It was Rehman's voice. It was quiet now, the thick, drunk anger of the hotel terrace gone, replaced by a dry, hollow rattle.

"Rehman," Vikram said. "Where are you?"

"I am in Alipore," the boy said.

"Come to Bagbazar. The lawyer has sent the signed deeds."

A long silence followed down the line. The sound of city traffic, distant and light, came through the receiver.

"I cannot come, uncle," the boy said.

"Why?"

"I looked at the signature on the copy," Rehman said, his voice dropping. "The blue blur at the end. You didn't even read the clauses before signing."

"The clauses don't change the decision, Rehman."

"I am ashamed, uncle," the boy whispered. "I said those terrible things on the terrace. The candle, the sun. It was the whiskey."

"It is alright."

"It is not," Rehman said. "I cannot look at your face. I will handle the Barasat work from my Alipore office. Don't call me."

The line went dead, the dial tone returning in a dry hum. Vikram held the receiver for a minute, listening to the mechanical drone, before placing it back on the hook.

---

Rehman didn't call the next week, or the week after that. By the end of December, the manager of the Barasat unit called the Bagbazar house.

"Vikram babu," the manager said. "The salary release is pending. Rehman sir hasn't signed the bank authorization for the monthly wages."

"Is he not in Alipore?" Vikram asked.

"The apartment is locked, sir. The security guard said he left with two bags on Tuesday night. He took a local cab to the railway station."

Vikram took his small bag. He went to Alipore himself.

The apartment building was tall, the concrete walls painted cream, with large glass balconies reflecting the cold winter sun. The security guard, an old Gorkha named Thapa, was sitting on a red plastic chair near the gate. 

He recognized Vikram from the newspaper photos immediately. "Rehman saab left," Thapa said.

"When?"

"Tuesday night, sir. He had two blue bags with him—the ones with the rusted zips."

"Did he leave an address?"

"No, sir. He just said he was going to Cuttack. He looked very sick, Vikram saab. His eyes were very dry, like he hadn't slept for weeks."

Vikram stood near the gate, looking at the parking slots. 

A silver sedan, identical to the one Rehman had driven, was parked near the compound wall. It was covered in a thick layer of grey city dust, and someone had traced a name into the dirt of the rear glass window with a finger: *Ummed.*

He looked at the dusty window. The Alipore house was locked, the silver sedan was empty, and Rehman was gone.

